006=3D"" class=3D"introduction h4">
      What Are the Differences Between Variance and Standard Deviation?
    </h3> <p data-v-6b5e7006=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins"><span data-v-6b5=
e7006=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">Variance</span> and <a data-v-6b5e7006=3D=
"" href=3D"https://statisticscalculators.com/standard-deviation-calculator"=
 class=3D"" target=3D"_blank">
        standard deviation
      </a> are two of the most common <a data-v-6b5e7006=3D"" href=3D"https=
://365datascience.com/tutorials/statistics-tutorials/coefficient-variation-=
variance-standard-deviation/" target=3D"_blank">
        measures of variability
      </a>.
    </p> <p data-v-6b5e7006=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      We define variance as the average of the squared deviations around th=
e mean. But, since this measure is expressed in squared units, it can be di=
fficult to interpret and compare across multiple datasets. Therefore, we ne=
ed a way to translate it back to the original units of measurement.
    </p> <p data-v-6b5e7006=3D"" class=3D"bottom-margins">
      This is where <span data-v-6b5e7006=3D"" class=3D"bolded-texts">stand=
ard deviation</span> comes in. We define it as the square root of the varia=
nce, and express it in the same units as the original data. This measure of=
 spread is more straightforward than variance because of its direct interpr=
etation in the same unit as the observations. Consequently, we use standard=
 deviation more regularly, particularly when it comes to practical applicat=
ions such as data analysis, reporting, and decision-making.
    </p> <p data-v-6b5e7006=3D"">
      You can use our Variance Calculator and <a data-v-6b5e7006=3D"" href=
=3D"https://statisticscalculators.com/standard-deviation-calculator" class=
=3D"" target=3D"_blank">
        Standard Deviation Calculator
      </a> to obtain both.
